<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Recall that:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
          <em>The Mean Value Theorem</em> states that if we have a function <m>f</m> which is continuous in the interval <m>[a,b]</m> and differentiable in <m>(a,b)</m>, then whenever <m>x_1,x_2\in[a,b]</m> and <m>x_1\neq x_2</m>, we have a point <m>c\in(x_1,x_2)</m> such that
          <me> f(x_2)-f(x_1) = f'(c) (x_2-x_1)</me>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p> a function, <m>g</m>, is <em>strictly increasing</em> if whenever we have <m>x_1 \lt x_2</m> we also have <m>g(x_1) \lt g(x_2)</m>.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      Use The Mean Value Theorem to show that if <m>f</m> is a differentiable function and the derivative of <m>f</m> is positive everywhere, then <m>f</m> is a strictly increasing function.
    </p>

  </statement>
  <answer>
    <proof>
      <p>
      Assume that <m>f</m> is a differentiable function and its derivative is positive everywhere. Also assume that <m>x_1, x_2\in\mathbb{R}</m> and <m>x_1 \lt x_2</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
       By <em>The Mean Value Theorem</em>, we know that <m>f(x_2)-f(x_1) = f'(c)(x_2-x_1)</m> for some <m>c\in(x_1,x_2)</m>. Since the derivative is positive everywhere, we know that <m>f'(c) \gt 0</m>, and since <m>x_2 \gt x_1</m> we also know that <m>(x_2-x_1)\gt 0</m>. Hence <m>f(x_2)-f(x_1) = f'(c)(x_2-x_1) \gt 0 </m> and <m>f(x_2)\gt f(x_1)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>Therefore <m>f</m> is a strictly increasing function.</p>
      </proof>
  </answer>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <alert>Definition:</alert> We call a number <m>n</m> an <term>integer root</term> when  <m>n^k=m</m> for some <m>k\in \mathbb{N}</m> and <m>m \in \mathbb{Z}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>Use this definition to show that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are integer roots, then so is <m>ab</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>Notice that every integer <m>t</m> is an integer root since we can take <m>k=1</m> and <m>m=t</m> as given in the definition. But an integer root does not have to be an integer, since numbers such as <m>\sqrt[3]{7}</m> is an integer root; take <m>k=3</m> and <m>m=7</m> as given in the definition.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <answer>
    <proof>
      <p>Assume that <m>a, b</m> are integer roots, then, by definition, there are natural numbers <m>k,l</m> and integers <m>m,s</m> such that <m>a^k=n</m> and <m>b^l=m</m>.
      Therefore we see that <m>(ab)^{kl}=n^lm^k</m>.
      Since <m>kl\in\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>n^lm^k\in\mathbb{Z}</m>, we see that <m>ab</m> is also an integer root.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </answer>
</exercise>
</exercises>
